<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-316-636  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 316 636.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  March 19 1990 v4 n11 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Contractors petition OMB for Byrd revisions; vendors sayamendment's guidance remains unclear. (Office of Management andBudget is asked to clarify its guidance to contractorimplementation of the 1990 Interior Appropriations Act amendmentregulating contractor behavior)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Marsan, Carolyn Duffy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Council of Defense and Space Industry Associations (CODSIA)and the US Chamber of Commerce (COC) asked the US Office ofManagement and Budget (OMB) to revise its guidance to companieswho must implement Byrd Amendment (a part of the 1990 InteriorAppropriations Act) regulations for government contractors.andP;  Theamendment requires that all firms that receive more than $100,000worth of federal contracts, loans or grants sign a certificationthat they have not and will not use federal funds for lobbying.andO;The firms must sign a disclosure of all non-federal fees paid tolobbyists in lieu of using federal funds.andP;  Violation of theregulations may result in fines ranging from $10,000 to $100,000for each offense.andP;  The CODSIA and COD asked the OMB to rewrite itsimplementing regulations to identify all specific activities wherethe rules apply.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     LegislationImplementationGovernment RegulationContractorsGovernment ContractsPerformanceRequirements AnalysisLobbyingLimitationsUnited States. Office of Management and Budget.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>